"4 July 1369":"4 juli 1369","1362":"1362","1350":"1350","1283":"1283","1293":"1293","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1369":"1369","1399":"1399","1343":"1343","1453":"1453","1365":"1365","about 1315":"circa 1315","1309":"1309","1307":"1307","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Yorkshire, England",", York, England":"York, North Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Egremont, Cumberland, England":"Egremont, Cumberland, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Cockermouth, Cumberland, England":"Cockermouth, Cumberland, England","Cumberland, England":"Cumberland, England","England, United Kingdom":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1315–4 July 1369":"about 1315–4 July 1369","1309–1365":"1309–1365","1315–1369":"1315–1369","–Female":"Deceased","1317–1362":"1317–1362","1350–1399":"1350–1399","1283–1343":"1283–1343","1293–1343":"1293–1343","10 Jun 1343":"18 June 1343","4 July 1369":"4 July 1369","1362":"1362","1350":"1350","1283":"1283","1293":"1293","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1369":"1369","1399":"1399","1343":"1343","1453":"1453","1365":"1365","about 1315":"about 1315","1309":"1309","1307":"1307","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Yorkshire, England",", York, England":"York, North Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Egremont, Cumberland, England":"Egremont, Cumberland, England, United Kingdom","Cockermouth, Cumberland, England":"Cockermouth, Cumberland, England","Cumberland, England":"Cumberland, England","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Lucy","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Irish and English: variant of   Lucey  .","French: habitational name from any of various places called Lucy, originally named with the Latin personal name <i>Lucius</i> + the locative suffix <i>-acum</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Lucey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Maeve, Niall.","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Luasaigh</b>, an altered form of <b>Mac Cluasaigh</b>, a Cork name meaning ‘son of <i>Cluasach</i>’, a byname originally denoting someone with large or otherwise noticeable ears (from <i>cluas</i> ‘ear’).","English: variant of   Luce   1."]}]},{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":0,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":13,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":22,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Joan Lucy was born about 1315, in Egremont, Cumberland, England, her father, Anthony de Lucy, was 34 and her mother, Elizabeth de Tilliol, was 24. She had at least 1 son with Sir William de Melton. She died on 4 July 1369, in York, North Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 55."},"et":{"about 1315–4 July 1369":"umbes 1315–4. juuli 1369","1309–1365":"1309–1365","1315–1369":"1315–1369","–Female":"Surnud","1317–1362":"1317–1362","1350–1399":"1350–1399","1283–1343":"1283–1343","1293–1343":"1293–1343","10 Jun 1343":"18. juuni 1343","4 July 1369":"4. juuli 1369","1362":"1362","1350":"1350","1283":"1283","1293":"1293","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1369":"1369","1399":"1399","1343":"1343","1453":"1453","1365":"1365","about 1315":"umbes 1315","1309":"1309","1307":"1307","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Yorkshire, England",", York, England":"York, North Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Egremont, Cumberland, England":"Egremont, Cumberland, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Cockermouth, Cumberland, England":"Cockermouth